2
00:00:48,048 --> 00:00:51,150
My friend Nicholas Brady, who in
his own way tried to save the

3
00:00:51,152 --> 00:00:55,521
world, lived in Berkeley
practically his whole life.

4
00:00:55,523 --> 00:00:59,491
Back around 1985, Berkeley,
California seemed like an oasis

5
00:00:59,493 --> 00:01:03,128
in a country that had become
polarized and divided.

6
00:01:03,130 --> 00:01:06,231
But Fate or God or
whatever had something else

7
00:01:06,233 --> 00:01:08,500
in store for my
friend Nick

8
00:01:08,502 --> 00:01:12,538
and as it turned out,
for me, too.

9
00:01:20,480 --> 00:01:23,615
Look, Nick, I appreciate your
interest in the business,

10
00:01:23,617 --> 00:01:26,452
but these compact discs
aren't going to catch on.

11
00:01:26,454 --> 00:01:28,520
Not with our customers.

12
00:01:28,522 --> 00:01:29,755
Why not?

13
00:01:29,757 --> 00:01:32,324
That digital sound
is too perfect.

14
00:01:32,326 --> 00:01:33,625
It's cold.

15
00:01:33,627 --> 00:01:35,360
Metallic.

16
00:01:35,362 --> 00:01:38,263
Don't underestimate
the human element.

17
00:01:38,265 --> 00:01:41,200
Even if CDs catch on, the
records here will

18
00:01:41,202 --> 00:01:43,535
be worth a fortune.

19
00:01:43,537 --> 00:01:46,438
Or nothing at all.

20
00:01:46,440 --> 00:01:48,240
Life's a gamble.

21
00:01:48,242 --> 00:01:50,242
Be patient.

22
00:01:50,244 --> 00:01:52,578
One day it's all
going to be yours

23
00:01:52,580 --> 00:01:57,416
and Rachel's, then you
can do what you like.

24
00:02:02,388 --> 00:02:07,559
♪ I wanna destroy you ♪

25
00:02:09,562 --> 00:02:13,265
♪ A pox upon the media ♪

26
00:02:13,267 --> 00:02:17,236
♪ And everything
you read ♪

27
00:02:17,238 --> 00:02:20,139
♪ They tell you
your opinions ♪

28
00:02:20,141 --> 00:02:25,144
♪ And they're very
good indeed ♪

29
00:02:25,146 --> 00:02:32,417
♪ I wanna destroy you ♪

30
00:02:32,419 --> 00:02:35,454
♪ When I have
destroyed you ♪

31
00:02:35,456 --> 00:02:40,259
♪ I'll come picking
at your bones ♪

32
00:02:40,261 --> 00:02:44,163
♪ And you won't have
a single atom ♪

33
00:02:44,165 --> 00:02:47,666
♪ Left to call
your own ♪

34
00:04:22,662 --> 00:04:24,396
Hey.

35
00:04:24,398 --> 00:04:26,398
Phil just called and
he's on his way over.

36
00:04:26,400 --> 00:04:28,634
Please don't tell
him about last night.

37
00:04:28,636 --> 00:04:31,637
Promise?

38
00:04:31,639 --> 00:04:34,339
Mm.

39
00:04:38,544 --> 00:04:40,545
Muah.

40
00:04:40,547 --> 00:04:41,713
Have a good day.

41
00:04:41,715 --> 00:04:44,616
Bye, baby.

42
00:04:44,618 --> 00:04:46,551
Sorry, I'm late.

43
00:04:46,553 --> 00:04:49,721
My cat got run over
by a truck yesterday.

44
00:04:49,723 --> 00:04:52,190
That's the bad news.

45
00:04:52,192 --> 00:04:54,526
What's the good news?

46
00:04:54,528 --> 00:04:56,762
My new novel,
getting published.

47
00:04:56,764 --> 00:04:58,530
In hardcover this time.

48
00:04:58,532 --> 00:05:00,332
Oh, wow, that's
great, man.

49
00:05:00,334 --> 00:05:01,700
Which one?

50
00:05:01,702 --> 00:05:03,368
The one about what
might have happened

51
00:05:03,370 --> 00:05:07,773
if the Nazis won
the war.

52
00:05:07,775 --> 00:05:09,741
I have an idea you might
be interested in.

53
00:05:09,743 --> 00:05:15,714
Last night, I woke up and I saw
me staring down at myself.

54
00:05:15,716 --> 00:05:18,717
I think Rachel saw it,
too, but now she's not sure.

55
00:05:18,719 --> 00:05:20,285
That's weird.

56
00:05:20,287 --> 00:05:22,254
Were you high?

57
00:05:22,256 --> 00:05:24,556
You know I don't
smoke anymore.

58
00:05:24,558 --> 00:05:27,993
I think it was
a future me.

59
00:05:27,995 --> 00:05:31,396
Could something like that
be possible, time travel?

60
00:05:31,398 --> 00:05:34,700
It seemed like I was there to
help me or warn me or something.

61
00:05:34,702 --> 00:05:36,702
Might be.

62
00:05:36,704 --> 00:05:38,303
Did you look any older?

63
00:05:38,305 --> 00:05:40,472
No, I looked
exactly the same.

64
00:05:40,474 --> 00:05:43,375
Maybe it was an alternate self
communicating with you from an

65
00:05:43,377 --> 00:05:45,477
alternate universe.

66
00:05:45,479 --> 00:05:47,579
Can you use the idea?

67
00:05:47,581 --> 00:05:49,581
Nope, too ordinary.

68
00:05:49,583 --> 00:05:50,716
Too ordinary, huh?

69
00:05:50,718 --> 00:05:54,720
Well, that's--
that's me.

70
00:05:54,722 --> 00:05:56,521
Cheer up.

71
00:05:56,523 --> 00:05:58,724
You're still having
a better day than my cat.

72
00:05:58,726 --> 00:06:02,761
And so, while the membership
lists were destroyed prior

73
00:06:02,763 --> 00:06:05,330
to the collapse of
the Soviet Union,

74
00:06:05,332 --> 00:06:07,599
the code name for this
organization has been given

75
00:06:07,601 --> 00:06:10,402
to us by our new
Russian allies.

76
00:06:10,404 --> 00:06:13,071
That name is Aramchek,

77
00:06:13,073 --> 00:06:16,441
an agency of treason
and subversion.

78
00:06:16,443 --> 00:06:18,009
Aramchek.

79
00:06:18,011 --> 00:06:20,011
Remember that name.

80
00:06:20,013 --> 00:06:24,015
This secret organization
refuses to acknowledge that

81
00:06:24,017 --> 00:06:26,785
democracy and free
enterprise have triumphed.

82
00:06:26,787 --> 00:06:29,755
Instead, they would
turn back the clock,

83
00:06:29,757 --> 00:06:32,991
lead America into a dark
shadowy future of a godless

84
00:06:32,993 --> 00:06:35,060
dictatorship.

85
00:06:35,062 --> 00:06:39,264
In the near future, I intend to
report to you, the American

86
00:06:39,266 --> 00:06:44,770
people, the progress of our war
on this cadre of evildoers.

87
00:06:44,772 --> 00:06:47,773
In the meantime,
good night,

88
00:06:47,775 --> 00:06:52,077
and may God bless the
United States of America.

89
00:06:52,079 --> 00:06:54,446
The President's address this
evening contained a real

90
00:06:54,448 --> 00:06:56,481
bombshell,
didn't it Hugh?

91
00:06:56,483 --> 00:06:59,050
And I wouldn't be surprised if
this new crisis didn't have

92
00:06:59,052 --> 00:07:02,087
some bearing on President
Fremont's decision whether or

93
00:07:02,089 --> 00:07:06,425
not to seek an unprecedented
fifth term in office--

94
00:07:06,427 --> 00:07:08,627
15 years in office.

95
00:07:08,629 --> 00:07:10,462
You'd think that would
be enough for anyone.

96
00:07:10,464 --> 00:07:12,531
Not Fremont.

97
00:07:12,533 --> 00:07:16,468
The only way you get him out of
the Oval Office is in a casket.

98
00:07:32,585 --> 00:07:37,055
A record store clerk in Berkeley
will have many troubles.

99
00:07:37,057 --> 00:07:41,626
When he moves to Los Angeles,
he will find what he's been

100
00:07:41,628 --> 00:07:45,096
searching for
his entire life.

101
00:07:54,073 --> 00:07:57,008
I've had the strangest feeling
the last couple of days.

102
00:07:57,010 --> 00:08:01,012
It's like I've been asleep
my whole life waiting for

103
00:08:01,014 --> 00:08:04,049
something to happen.

104
00:08:04,051 --> 00:08:07,152
We gotta get out
of Berkeley.

105
00:08:07,154 --> 00:08:11,056
And how do you
plan on that?

106
00:08:11,058 --> 00:08:15,060
I'm thinking of
applying for a new job.

107
00:08:15,062 --> 00:08:16,595
I've already started talking to
some of the record company reps

108
00:08:16,597 --> 00:08:19,531
down in LA.

109
00:08:26,005 --> 00:08:29,541
Maybe they're just
ordinary dreams.

110
00:08:30,443 --> 00:08:32,210
Night after night?

111
00:08:32,212 --> 00:08:33,745
The images always appears
between 3:00 and 4:00

112
00:08:33,747 --> 00:08:36,081
in the morning.

113
00:08:36,083 --> 00:08:38,049
I think I'm being
programmed in my sleep.

114
00:08:38,051 --> 00:08:39,584
Just because I write science-
fiction, doesn't mean I believe

115
00:08:39,586 --> 00:08:41,186
in any of that stuff.

116
00:08:41,188 --> 00:08:46,024
I don't even think flying
saucers are real.

117
00:08:46,026 --> 00:08:50,061
I think a higher intelligence
has seen my needs and is

118
00:08:50,063 --> 00:08:52,097
directing me towards
something important,

119
00:08:52,099 --> 00:08:55,734
some extraordinary goal.

120
00:08:59,772 --> 00:09:02,541
So, a powerful
entity guiding you,

121
00:09:02,543 --> 00:09:04,609
helping you get
your shit together?

122
00:09:04,611 --> 00:09:06,578
Sounds good, what do
you think it is?

123
00:09:06,580 --> 00:09:08,146
Don't laugh, but I've
got a name for it.

124
00:09:08,148 --> 00:09:11,149
I call it VALIS.

125
00:09:11,151 --> 00:09:13,184
VALIS?

126
00:09:13,186 --> 00:09:19,090
It's an acronym for Vast Active
Living Intelligent System,

127
00:09:19,092 --> 00:09:24,129
because that's exactly what
it is and how I think of it.

128
00:09:24,131 --> 00:09:26,097
Does this VALIS provide
you with any clues

129
00:09:26,099 --> 00:09:29,467
as to your
amazing destiny?

130
00:09:29,469 --> 00:09:30,635
I don't have any choice
other than to believe it.

131
00:09:30,637 --> 00:09:35,140
I already got
a job offer.

132
00:09:35,142 --> 00:09:37,442
Progressive Records is the
first company I applied to,

133
00:09:37,444 --> 00:09:41,079
that's got
to mean something.

134
00:09:41,081 --> 00:09:42,781
Just one problem.

135
00:09:42,783 --> 00:09:46,117
What's that?

136
00:09:46,119 --> 00:09:49,120
I hate Los Angeles.

137
00:09:49,122 --> 00:09:51,056
Just for the sake of argument,
let's suppose it's something

138
00:09:51,058 --> 00:09:54,492
evil like the voices
that told Mark Chapman

139
00:09:54,494 --> 00:09:57,095
to shoot Mick Jagger.

140
00:09:57,097 --> 00:10:00,098
VALIS has a destiny
for me in LA.

141
00:10:00,100 --> 00:10:01,733
What am I supposed
to say to that?

142
00:10:01,735 --> 00:10:03,134
This is real.

143
00:10:03,136 --> 00:10:06,738
This is happening to me.

144
00:10:06,740 --> 00:10:09,140
Maybe it's
a precognition.

145
00:10:09,142 --> 00:10:12,510
Knowing what you're going
to do before you do it.

146
00:10:12,512 --> 00:10:14,479
I wrote a story
about that, remember?

147
00:10:14,481 --> 00:10:15,780
"The World Jones Made"?

148
00:10:15,782 --> 00:10:17,148
Vaguely.

149
00:10:17,150 --> 00:10:19,117
How'd that turn out?

150
00:10:19,119 --> 00:10:21,152
Not so good.

151
00:10:21,154 --> 00:10:24,155
Instead of being this wonderful
talent, being able to see a year

152
00:10:24,157 --> 00:10:29,094
into the future, it locked
Jones into a closed loop.

153
00:10:29,096 --> 00:10:31,262
He lost free choice.

154
00:10:31,264 --> 00:10:33,131
What do you mean?

155
00:10:33,133 --> 00:10:35,200
Well, since everything
was pre-determined,

156
00:10:35,202 --> 00:10:39,237
he was forced to act
out his own future.

157
00:10:39,239 --> 00:10:41,506
You foresee yourself
moving to LA.

158
00:10:41,508 --> 00:10:44,009
So now you're moving.

159
00:10:44,011 --> 00:10:46,211
You still don't
understand.

160
00:10:50,182 --> 00:10:53,084
VALIS knows about you.

161
00:10:53,086 --> 00:10:57,555
I was instructed to tell
you what's happening.

162
00:10:59,492 --> 00:11:02,193
You're putting me on.

163
00:11:07,500 --> 00:11:11,169
It's crazy, Nick.

164
00:11:11,171 --> 00:11:13,705
We're leaving Berkeley
because some imaginary voice

165
00:11:13,707 --> 00:11:18,209
tells you to uproot
our lives?

166
00:11:18,211 --> 00:11:21,312
It's not a practical way to
make a life-changing decision.

167
00:11:21,314 --> 00:11:23,548
What's better?

168
00:11:23,550 --> 00:11:26,217
Columbus listening to the
imaginary voices in his head

169
00:11:26,219 --> 00:11:30,055
that said "keep sailing" or the
real voices that said it was

170
00:11:30,057 --> 00:11:33,692
all hopeless
and doomed.

171
00:11:33,694 --> 00:11:36,227
Aren't results
what matter?

172
00:11:50,743 --> 00:11:55,146
See you guys
after lunch.

173
00:11:57,049 --> 00:12:00,218
Hey, Phil!

174
00:12:00,220 --> 00:12:02,253
I was starting to think you were
going to miss our last day!

175
00:12:02,255 --> 00:12:04,289
What, are you kidding?
Not a chance.

176
00:12:04,291 --> 00:12:07,325
I even brought
refreshments.

177
00:12:07,327 --> 00:12:10,128
Hi.

178
00:12:12,064 --> 00:12:13,198
So.

179
00:12:13,200 --> 00:12:15,734
None for me thanks.

180
00:12:15,736 --> 00:12:18,269
That's the first drink
I've ever seen you refuse.

181
00:12:18,271 --> 00:12:20,271
Did VALIS tell you to
go on the wagon?

182
00:12:20,273 --> 00:12:22,307
As a matter
of fact, yes.

183
00:12:22,309 --> 00:12:25,176
Oh, come on, baby,
lighten up.

184
00:12:25,178 --> 00:12:26,277
You know, I've been trying
to get him to cut back

185
00:12:26,279 --> 00:12:28,146
on alcohol for years.

186
00:12:28,148 --> 00:12:30,281
His wife, he ignores, but one
little word from the Big Mind

187
00:12:30,283 --> 00:12:32,117
in the sky...

188
00:12:32,119 --> 00:12:35,253
All right,
okay, enough.

189
00:12:39,759 --> 00:12:41,159
To friendship.

190
00:12:41,161 --> 00:12:43,061
To Los Angeles.

191
00:12:43,063 --> 00:12:45,230
To destiny.

192
00:12:45,232 --> 00:12:47,265
Destiny.

193
00:12:52,338 --> 00:12:55,740
Oh God, excuse me.

194
00:12:59,311 --> 00:13:02,046
Could he get
any weirder?

195
00:13:02,048 --> 00:13:05,283
How are you supposed to
relate to a friend whose life

196
00:13:05,285 --> 00:13:08,286
is directed from
beyond the stars?

197
00:13:08,288 --> 00:13:11,256
I mean, what kind of attitude
am I supposed to take to that?

198
00:13:11,258 --> 00:13:14,325
Imagine being his wife.

199
00:13:14,327 --> 00:13:16,261
It's taken over your
lives, hasn't it?

200
00:13:16,263 --> 00:13:19,030
And the strange part is,
VALIS is doing a better job

201
00:13:19,032 --> 00:13:21,132
than we ever did.

202
00:13:21,134 --> 00:13:23,168
I've never seen
Nick so....

203
00:13:23,170 --> 00:13:25,336
Motivated.

204
00:13:25,338 --> 00:13:28,239
It's like he's an entirely
different person.

205
00:13:28,241 --> 00:13:32,210
Yeah.

206
00:13:41,320 --> 00:13:46,024
I've been thinking
about leaving him.

207
00:13:47,426 --> 00:13:49,360
Wow.

208
00:13:49,362 --> 00:13:52,030
What did you decide?

209
00:13:52,032 --> 00:13:56,668
The decision has
been made for me.

210
00:13:56,670 --> 00:14:01,306
I saw a gynecologist
last week.

211
00:14:01,308 --> 00:14:04,209
I'm pregnant.

212
00:14:09,081 --> 00:14:12,350
That's wonderful.

213
00:14:12,352 --> 00:14:16,020
I haven't told Nick.

214
00:14:16,022 --> 00:14:17,355
Okay.

215
00:14:17,357 --> 00:14:21,426
I'm scared about
everything.

216
00:14:25,364 --> 00:14:28,333
Tell me it's all
going to be okay.

217
00:14:28,335 --> 00:14:30,201
Of course.

218
00:14:30,203 --> 00:14:32,704
Of course it's
gonna be okay.

219
00:14:35,341 --> 00:14:39,177
Though the Cold War may be over,
as you know, the secret

220
00:14:39,179 --> 00:14:43,214
organization Aramchek is still
committed to undermining our

221
00:14:43,216 --> 00:14:46,084
democratic institutions.

222
00:14:46,086 --> 00:14:50,021
Accordingly, I have instructed
our Attorney General to prepare

223
00:14:50,023 --> 00:14:54,025
the appropriate legislation to
amend those First Amendment

224
00:14:54,027 --> 00:14:57,328
rights that have been so long
abused by our country's foes

225
00:14:57,330 --> 00:15:01,466
and their unwitting allies
among the media elite.

226
00:15:01,468 --> 00:15:08,106
No one regrets these measures
more than your President.

227
00:15:08,108 --> 00:15:11,242
And so, following the
instructions of VALIS,

228
00:15:11,244 --> 00:15:14,345
my friends Nick and Rachel
moved down to LA.

229
00:15:14,347 --> 00:15:18,116
I thought of them often, but
it was more than a year until

230
00:15:18,118 --> 00:15:21,119
I took the eight-hour bus ride
down from Berkeley.

231
00:15:23,055 --> 00:15:24,422
Excuse me, sir.

232
00:15:24,424 --> 00:15:27,158
Can I give you
the good news?

233
00:15:37,770 --> 00:15:39,504
Jesus Christ.

234
00:15:39,506 --> 00:15:41,372
I never thought
I'd see the day.

235
00:15:41,374 --> 00:15:44,175
An old socialist like you
driving around in a Beamer.

236
00:15:51,517 --> 00:15:53,017
You look great.

237
00:15:53,019 --> 00:15:54,118
Yeah?

238
00:15:54,120 --> 00:15:56,754
LA seems to
agree with you.

239
00:15:56,756 --> 00:15:59,324
Still doing your art?

240
00:15:59,326 --> 00:16:01,426
No, not so much.

241
00:16:01,428 --> 00:16:06,097
I've been really busy,
with the baby and all.

242
00:16:06,099 --> 00:16:07,298
How's Nick?

243
00:16:07,300 --> 00:16:09,133
Oh, he's-- he's great.

244
00:16:09,135 --> 00:16:10,468
He loves it here, too.

245
00:16:10,470 --> 00:16:12,437
You know, he wanted
to pick you up himself,

246
00:16:12,439 --> 00:16:15,406
but he's in the studio with
one of his new groups.

247
00:16:15,408 --> 00:16:19,410
What about VALIS?

248
00:16:19,412 --> 00:16:22,013
Phil, look,
do me a favor.

249
00:16:22,015 --> 00:16:24,382
Don't bring up
that stuff.

250
00:16:25,517 --> 00:16:27,285
Wow.

251
00:16:27,287 --> 00:16:29,520
A far cry from
the record store, huh?

252
00:16:43,435 --> 00:16:45,303
Hey, Phil.

253
00:16:45,305 --> 00:16:46,337
Glad you could make it.

254
00:16:46,339 --> 00:16:48,373
Get in here.

255
00:16:50,309 --> 00:16:51,709
I want you to stick around
and check these guys out.

256
00:16:51,711 --> 00:16:54,345
I'm gonna get a producer
credit on this album,

257
00:16:54,347 --> 00:16:56,381
maybe a senior vice-presidency
if market research is right

258
00:16:56,383 --> 00:16:59,784
about these guys.

259
00:17:03,155 --> 00:17:05,523
You believing it?

260
00:17:05,525 --> 00:17:07,492
Believe what?

261
00:17:07,494 --> 00:17:11,529
All this, my act.

262
00:17:11,531 --> 00:17:13,498
What are you
talking about?

263
00:17:13,500 --> 00:17:16,034
So you bought it, too.

264
00:17:16,036 --> 00:17:19,170
That's good, that means I must
be doing something right.

265
00:17:33,352 --> 00:17:35,153
Check it out.

266
00:17:35,155 --> 00:17:39,557
This is an image that I've been
shown over and over again.

267
00:17:47,599 --> 00:17:49,567
What the hell?

268
00:17:49,569 --> 00:17:52,303
Was that lightning?

269
00:17:54,173 --> 00:17:55,506
Hey.

270
00:17:55,508 --> 00:17:57,075
Nick?

271
00:17:57,077 --> 00:17:59,343
Hey.

272
00:18:00,579 --> 00:18:03,214
You okay?

273
00:18:07,052 --> 00:18:09,287
I don't know why we
had to rush over here.

274
00:18:09,289 --> 00:18:11,189
Ezra's just fine.

275
00:18:11,191 --> 00:18:12,423
No, he's not,
I told you.

276
00:18:12,425 --> 00:18:15,560
He has a birth defect.

277
00:18:15,562 --> 00:18:16,794
Good morning.

278
00:18:16,796 --> 00:18:20,531
Hey, Doctor,
thank you for coming.

279
00:18:20,533 --> 00:18:23,534
He has an inguinal strangulated
hernia on the left side.

280
00:18:23,536 --> 00:18:26,537
It's already descended
into the scrotal sac.

281
00:18:26,539 --> 00:18:30,508
I'm used to parents imagining
dreadful diseases in the middle

282
00:18:30,510 --> 00:18:34,412
of the night, but rarely
with such specificity.

283
00:18:34,414 --> 00:18:38,082
I just saw Ezra
last week, but...

284
00:18:38,084 --> 00:18:41,552
It's okay, it's all right,
it's okay...

285
00:18:44,656 --> 00:18:48,126
Wait a second.

286
00:18:50,696 --> 00:18:52,396
Page Dr. Andrews, tell
him to come right in,

287
00:18:52,398 --> 00:18:55,099
it's an emergency.

288
00:18:58,437 --> 00:19:01,205
I don't know what to tell you,
it's exactly what you thought.

289
00:19:01,207 --> 00:19:02,240
Is he going
to be alright?

290
00:19:02,242 --> 00:19:03,441
Yeah, he'll be fine.

291
00:19:03,443 --> 00:19:05,143
It's a minor
problem to correct,

292
00:19:05,145 --> 00:19:06,544
but it's potentially
very dangerous.

293
00:19:06,546 --> 00:19:09,547
We caught it
just in time.

294
00:19:16,455 --> 00:19:18,356
Hey.

295
00:19:18,358 --> 00:19:19,657
How is he?

296
00:19:19,659 --> 00:19:22,727
Ezra's going
to be fine.

297
00:19:22,729 --> 00:19:25,296
What's going on?

298
00:19:25,298 --> 00:19:27,165
How did you know that?

299
00:19:27,167 --> 00:19:30,568
Was it VALIS?

300
00:19:30,570 --> 00:19:32,670
Let's get Ezra
and Rachel home first,

301
00:19:32,672 --> 00:19:35,339
then I'll fill you
in on everything.

302
00:19:43,615 --> 00:19:47,451
I'm always amazed at how much
difference the desert air makes.

303
00:19:47,453 --> 00:19:50,588
A lot cleaner than LA,
isn't it?

304
00:19:50,590 --> 00:19:55,326
No spies,
no police informers.

305
00:19:55,328 --> 00:19:59,597
Out here, the wind blows in
from the east and north.

306
00:19:59,599 --> 00:20:03,367
For some reason,
the signal's much stronger.

307
00:20:03,369 --> 00:20:07,305
I think VALIS is located
in our upper atmosphere.

308
00:20:07,307 --> 00:20:09,440
How is that
even possible?

309
00:20:09,442 --> 00:20:12,176
How could any kind of living
creature exist up there,

310
00:20:12,178 --> 00:20:13,477
survive?

311
00:20:13,479 --> 00:20:15,313
No, see, it's not--

312
00:20:15,315 --> 00:20:17,748
It's not a he or
she or even an it.

313
00:20:17,750 --> 00:20:20,284
It's a composite entity.

314
00:20:20,286 --> 00:20:23,621
It's as if various beings had
come together and formed

315
00:20:23,623 --> 00:20:27,491
a single body
and group mind.

316
00:20:27,493 --> 00:20:30,461
How do you know
all this?

317
00:20:30,463 --> 00:20:34,332
I've had dream after dream after
dream from their point of view.

318
00:20:34,334 --> 00:20:36,634
From way up,
looking down.

319
00:20:36,636 --> 00:20:41,372
To them earth is like this
horrible, stagnant pond and

320
00:20:41,374 --> 00:20:47,645
human beings just swim around
in the muck trying to survive.

321
00:20:47,647 --> 00:20:51,649
I think they're
anxious to help us.

322
00:20:51,651 --> 00:20:54,252
That doesn't make
sense to me.

323
00:20:54,254 --> 00:20:56,654
Highly evolved creature living
in the sky taking an active

324
00:20:56,656 --> 00:20:59,690
interest in
human welfare?

325
00:20:59,692 --> 00:21:01,559
Why would they?

326
00:21:01,561 --> 00:21:03,661
I think they feel
sorry for us.

327
00:21:03,663 --> 00:21:05,730
Try to imagine it.

328
00:21:05,732 --> 00:21:07,531
Advanced beings
living alongside

329
00:21:07,533 --> 00:21:10,401
the human race
throughout history,

330
00:21:10,403 --> 00:21:12,236
watching our wars
and famines,

331
00:21:12,238 --> 00:21:14,372
observing our
unbelievable cruelty,

332
00:21:14,374 --> 00:21:17,742
our unbelievable
stupidity.

333
00:21:19,011 --> 00:21:21,779
Wait a second, hold on.

334
00:21:23,715 --> 00:21:26,784
I'm getting new
instructions.

335
00:21:33,558 --> 00:21:37,395
You're never going to believe
where they want me to go.

336
00:21:37,397 --> 00:21:41,232
...So, this modest bungalow is
the house where the president

337
00:21:41,234 --> 00:21:44,201
actually grew up in
his formative years,

338
00:21:44,203 --> 00:21:47,405
the dwelling where our beloved
leader first did homework,

339
00:21:47,407 --> 00:21:50,541
first played basketball, first
read inspiring biographies

340
00:21:50,543 --> 00:21:52,376
of history's
greatest men.

341
00:22:18,704 --> 00:22:21,706
Don't worry,
there's no guards.

342
00:22:21,708 --> 00:22:24,608
I guess they figure
no one would dare trespass

343
00:22:24,610 --> 00:22:26,777
on the holiest
of holies.

344
00:22:26,779 --> 00:22:29,647
Maybe they
have a point.

345
00:22:31,416 --> 00:22:32,717
There it is.

346
00:22:32,719 --> 00:22:34,785
What's the big deal?

347
00:22:34,787 --> 00:22:36,687
It's just a signature
in the cement.

348
00:22:36,689 --> 00:22:38,789
Probably the name
of the contractor.

349
00:22:38,791 --> 00:22:41,525
Baby, look at it,
look at the name.

350
00:22:41,527 --> 00:22:43,794
It's a little faded and hard
to read, but you see it,

351
00:22:43,796 --> 00:22:46,030
right, Phil?

352
00:22:46,032 --> 00:22:50,000
I'm seeing it,
but I can't believe it.

353
00:22:50,002 --> 00:22:54,071
Aramchek.

354
00:22:54,073 --> 00:22:57,441
I get this urge to go
to the Fremont Museum.

355
00:22:57,443 --> 00:23:02,413
I wander away from
the group I see it.

356
00:23:02,415 --> 00:23:04,448
Then I realize,
I was meant to see it.

357
00:23:04,450 --> 00:23:05,750
Please don't tell me
you're starting up again

358
00:23:05,752 --> 00:23:07,585
with the whole
VALIS thing.

359
00:23:07,587 --> 00:23:12,456
Little Richard Fremont played in
that backyard and saw the name

360
00:23:12,458 --> 00:23:14,759
written in the
cement, Aramchek,

361
00:23:14,761 --> 00:23:17,795
and for whatever reason it
sticks in his little brain

362
00:23:17,797 --> 00:23:20,498
as something sinister.

363
00:23:20,500 --> 00:23:24,001
Once the boy grows up,
he projects his paranoia

364
00:23:24,003 --> 00:23:26,370
on the whole world.

365
00:23:26,372 --> 00:23:31,375
Aramchek, the super-secret
cabal of evil revolutionaries.

366
00:23:31,377 --> 00:23:34,678
it's a figment of
his imagination.

367
00:23:34,680 --> 00:23:37,114
A childhood memory.

368
00:23:37,116 --> 00:23:39,016
It's genius.

369
00:23:39,018 --> 00:23:41,652
The government declares war on
a terrorist organization that

370
00:23:41,654 --> 00:23:44,054
doesn't even exist.

371
00:23:44,056 --> 00:23:45,656
No one can
destroy it.

372
00:23:45,658 --> 00:23:48,626
No one's safe from it.

373
00:23:48,628 --> 00:23:50,361
No one knows when
it'll turn up again.

374
00:23:50,363 --> 00:23:54,031
What do you think
happened to Mr. Aramchek,

375
00:23:54,033 --> 00:23:56,000
Whoever he
actually was?

376
00:23:56,002 --> 00:23:58,636
He's dead.

377
00:23:58,638 --> 00:24:01,705
Or stuck away in some
rehabilitation camp.

378
00:24:01,707 --> 00:24:05,342
What else would you expect
from Richard Fremont?

379
00:24:09,714 --> 00:24:12,550
Do you really have
to go back to Berkeley?

380
00:24:12,552 --> 00:24:14,518
Yeah.

381
00:24:14,520 --> 00:24:17,021
I gotta finish my book.

382
00:24:17,023 --> 00:24:20,558
Besides, I can't be your house
guest forever, you know?

383
00:24:22,394 --> 00:24:27,431
It's gotten so...
weird all of a sudden.

384
00:24:29,100 --> 00:24:31,001
No, man, you--
you just--

385
00:24:31,003 --> 00:24:33,037
You do what
you need to do.

386
00:24:33,039 --> 00:24:35,039
We'll be fine.

387
00:24:35,041 --> 00:24:38,342
We have VALIS
to protect us.

388
00:24:38,344 --> 00:24:40,644
Back in Berkeley my life
returned to normal,

389
00:24:40,646 --> 00:24:42,513
which for me was
mostly work,

390
00:24:42,515 --> 00:24:45,082
staying up all night with
the help of amphetamines.

391
00:24:45,084 --> 00:24:47,017
While I was in LA, Nick and
I had spent hour after hour

392
00:24:47,019 --> 00:24:49,086
talking about VALIS,

393
00:24:49,088 --> 00:24:52,556
different theories about how it
operated, what it wanted,

394
00:24:52,558 --> 00:24:55,059
why it had come now.

395
00:24:55,061 --> 00:24:57,728
I had material for a dozen
stories just based on all

396
00:24:57,730 --> 00:25:00,564
the premises
we spun out,

397
00:25:00,566 --> 00:25:03,100
but none that I could write
about without betraying

398
00:25:03,102 --> 00:25:06,070
my friend's confidence.

399
00:25:11,776 --> 00:25:14,512
Gentlemen.

400
00:25:18,116 --> 00:25:20,417
What can I do for you?

401
00:25:20,419 --> 00:25:22,086
Are we putting out too
many protest songs?

402
00:25:22,088 --> 00:25:24,121
No, on the contrary,
Mr. Brady.

403
00:25:24,123 --> 00:25:25,589
May I call you Nick?

404
00:25:25,591 --> 00:25:27,458
Sure.

405
00:25:27,460 --> 00:25:29,593
Progressive has a very positive
rating with the Bureau, Nick.

406
00:25:29,595 --> 00:25:32,763
One of the best in the whole
recording industry.

407
00:25:32,765 --> 00:25:35,432
Just a precaution.

408
00:25:35,434 --> 00:25:37,101
You'd be surprised
how many otherwise decent,

409
00:25:37,103 --> 00:25:38,736
law-abiding Americans

410
00:25:38,738 --> 00:25:41,071
think it's necessary to tape
informal interrogations like

411
00:25:41,073 --> 00:25:45,075
this one.

412
00:25:45,077 --> 00:25:47,144
How can I help you?

413
00:25:47,146 --> 00:25:49,580
Actually, we're here
to help you, Nick.

414
00:25:49,582 --> 00:25:51,482
We happen to know you're
currently under a great deal

415
00:25:51,484 --> 00:25:54,084
of financial pressure.

416
00:25:54,086 --> 00:25:58,422
Your wife wants your son to go
to an exclusive nursery school.

417
00:25:58,424 --> 00:26:01,025
She also expects you to
put a large down payment

418
00:26:01,027 --> 00:26:04,028
on a much larger house.

419
00:26:04,030 --> 00:26:06,697
We're prepared to offer you
a simple, patriotic way

420
00:26:06,699 --> 00:26:10,067
to enhance your salary
by up to $2,000 a month.

421
00:26:10,069 --> 00:26:11,602
How does that
sound Nick?

422
00:26:11,604 --> 00:26:13,137
Tax free.

423
00:26:13,139 --> 00:26:15,105
Not even reportable.

424
00:26:15,107 --> 00:26:19,043
I'm flattered you'd thought
of me but honestly, I have a--

425
00:26:19,045 --> 00:26:20,110
Are you turning your country
down before you even know

426
00:26:20,112 --> 00:26:22,780
what we're asking?

427
00:26:22,782 --> 00:26:25,649
Maybe your loyalty evaluation
needs to be updated.

428
00:26:25,651 --> 00:26:27,685
Wouldn't take any
extra work at all.

429
00:26:27,687 --> 00:26:31,221
It's a function of work
you're already doing.

430
00:26:33,124 --> 00:26:34,191
All right, I'll listen.

431
00:26:34,193 --> 00:26:36,226
It's very
simple, really.

432
00:26:36,228 --> 00:26:39,163
See, despite the generally
cooperative attitude of radio

433
00:26:39,165 --> 00:26:42,533
stations and music executives
like yourself,

434
00:26:42,535 --> 00:26:44,568
a number of anti-social
protest songs

435
00:26:44,570 --> 00:26:47,471
are still
getting airplay...

436
00:26:51,176 --> 00:26:53,177
Subject Nicholas Brady refused
to cooperate with the current

437
00:26:53,179 --> 00:26:55,179
investigation.

438
00:26:55,181 --> 00:26:57,147
The following is
a transcript of the conversation

439
00:26:57,149 --> 00:26:59,216
taped with the subject.

440
00:26:59,218 --> 00:27:01,619
Recommendation is for this file
to be sent to Washington

441
00:27:01,621 --> 00:27:04,221
for inclusion in
Project Coliseum.

442
00:27:04,223 --> 00:27:06,523
What can I do
for you?

443
00:27:06,525 --> 00:27:08,158
Are we putting out too
many protest songs?

444
00:27:08,160 --> 00:27:11,095
No, on the contrary,
Mr. Brady.

445
00:27:36,087 --> 00:27:40,290
So you're certain nothing of
actual monetary value was taken?

446
00:27:40,292 --> 00:27:42,159
Yeah, just
some papers.

447
00:27:42,161 --> 00:27:45,062
Notes for my
new novel.

448
00:27:45,064 --> 00:27:47,765
Fortunately, I've got a copy
that I keep with a friend.

449
00:27:47,767 --> 00:27:50,534
Well, that seems like
a strange practice.

450
00:27:50,536 --> 00:27:52,236
It's almost as if you were
anticipating some kind

451
00:27:52,238 --> 00:27:54,071
of problem like this.

452
00:27:54,073 --> 00:27:55,105
Not really.

453
00:27:55,107 --> 00:27:57,641
It's just, uh...

454
00:28:04,049 --> 00:28:07,184
I've been told you write some
very far-out science fiction.

455
00:28:07,186 --> 00:28:10,187
Are you willing to testify under
oath that this isn't some kind

456
00:28:10,189 --> 00:28:13,257
of crazy
publicity stunt?
Are you suggesting--

457
00:28:13,259 --> 00:28:16,260
I'm not suggesting anything, but
we're inclined to believe you

458
00:28:16,262 --> 00:28:18,562
staged this
break-in yourself.
Yeah?

459
00:28:18,564 --> 00:28:21,331
Why would I trash my own house
and ransack my own files?

460
00:28:21,333 --> 00:28:23,734
What better way to throw
suspicion off yourself?

461
00:28:23,736 --> 00:28:25,703
Suspicion?
Suspicion of what?

462
00:28:25,705 --> 00:28:28,172
That's what we're going to
need to investigate further.

463
00:28:28,174 --> 00:28:30,140
I hope you'll make yourself
available for further

464
00:28:30,142 --> 00:28:31,308
questioning, if necessary.

465
00:28:31,310 --> 00:28:33,243
No, I'm going home.

466
00:28:33,245 --> 00:28:35,779
Forget about the burglary,
forget about the police report.

467
00:28:35,781 --> 00:28:40,350
A little late
for that, sir.

468
00:28:40,352 --> 00:28:44,188
You almost can't blame the
government for being curious.

469
00:28:44,190 --> 00:28:47,224
Half your stories read like
they were written on acid.

470
00:28:47,226 --> 00:28:49,760
Your entire readership consists
of freaks and misfits.

471
00:28:49,762 --> 00:28:51,428
Okay.

472
00:28:51,430 --> 00:28:52,463
So they're curious, that
doesn't give them the right

473
00:28:52,465 --> 00:28:54,298
to break into my house.

474
00:28:54,300 --> 00:28:57,267
They probably just want to
know about your next novel.

475
00:28:57,269 --> 00:28:59,169
I'd like to know, too.

476
00:28:59,171 --> 00:29:01,371
It's called "Flow My Tears,
the Policeman Said."

477
00:29:01,373 --> 00:29:03,240
Sounds political.

478
00:29:03,242 --> 00:29:04,475
No.

479
00:29:04,477 --> 00:29:06,643
Well, sort of,
it's like all my stuff.

480
00:29:06,645 --> 00:29:08,278
Did they get
the manuscript?

481
00:29:08,280 --> 00:29:10,114
No, I sent it
to my lawyer.

482
00:29:10,116 --> 00:29:11,749
It's in his safe.

483
00:29:11,751 --> 00:29:13,617
I sent it over as soon
as I was finished.

484
00:29:13,619 --> 00:29:17,254
It's time for you
move down here.

485
00:29:17,256 --> 00:29:20,023
We should wait to talk
'til I get to LA.

486
00:29:20,025 --> 00:29:21,759
With any luck, this thing
will just blow over.

487
00:29:21,761 --> 00:29:23,594
Not likely.

488
00:29:23,596 --> 00:29:28,365
Once the authorities open a file
on someone, they never close it.

489
00:29:28,367 --> 00:29:31,268
I'll talk to you soon.

490
00:29:35,140 --> 00:29:38,108
My books were finally
finding an audience.

491
00:29:38,110 --> 00:29:41,311
I was getting solid
critical reviews too,

492
00:29:41,313 --> 00:29:43,413
especially on my really
insane novel,

493
00:29:43,415 --> 00:29:47,384
"The Three Stigmata
of Palmer Eldritch."

494
00:29:47,386 --> 00:29:49,319
The rumor got started that I'd
written it under the influence

495
00:29:49,321 --> 00:29:52,055
of LSD.

496
00:29:55,193 --> 00:29:57,027
The notoriety had undoubtedly
brought me to the attention

497
00:29:57,029 --> 00:29:58,796
of the authorities,

498
00:29:58,798 --> 00:30:01,799
but it had also
paid off in sales.

499
00:30:01,801 --> 00:30:04,134
I was able to make a down
payment on a small bungalow

500
00:30:04,136 --> 00:30:07,337
in the grungy Echo Park
area of LA.

501
00:30:07,339 --> 00:30:11,408
When I wasn't working, I went
back as usual to hanging out

502
00:30:11,410 --> 00:30:14,344
with Nick and Rachel.

503
00:30:17,715 --> 00:30:21,418
My fellow Americans, this
evening's report will deal with

504
00:30:21,420 --> 00:30:25,355
the remarkable progress we've
made this quarter with our
domestic

505
00:30:25,357 --> 00:30:28,258
exports, despite
a temporary setback

506
00:30:28,260 --> 00:30:31,195
in the agricultural
sector.

507
00:30:31,197 --> 00:30:34,431
The unforeseeable effects of
terrorism and subversion remain

508
00:30:34,433 --> 00:30:37,201
the only question
mark for our country's

509
00:30:37,203 --> 00:30:40,170
continued
economic health.

510
00:30:44,442 --> 00:30:47,077
You know, at first I thought
these test questions were easy,

511
00:30:47,079 --> 00:30:48,545
just to see if we're
paying attention,

512
00:30:48,547 --> 00:30:51,315
but once you actually start
thinking about them,

513
00:30:51,317 --> 00:30:53,584
they're kind of tricky.

514
00:30:53,586 --> 00:30:56,053
"If American citizens must

515
00:30:56,055 --> 00:30:58,388
give up certain liberties
in the fight for freedom

516
00:30:58,390 --> 00:31:00,224
does it mean
the country is,

